					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">I'm not entirely familiar with DMA on the Super NES, but if it's anything like DMA on the GBA, it's essentially hardware-accelerated memcpy. DMA destination allows each channel to be used to copy to OAM, VRAM, palette, different scrolling registers, etc. And OAM isn't mapped into the VRAM address space on the NES, Game Boy, or GBA either. Your question sounds like "why is $4014 on the NES not in the $2000 block?".</div>

